Part 1 - Distribution of Age, Sex, Birthday and ZipCode¶

Data Sources:

  1. Zip Code: United States ZIP Code Database (2005-2016)
    • Link: https://www.unitedstateszipcodes.org/zip-code-database/ (Free)
  2. Age and Sex: U.S. Census Bureau, Population Division
    • Link (Documentation): https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/technical-documentation/file-layouts/2010-2019/nc-est2019-agesex-res.pdf
    • Link (CSV): https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/technical-documentation/file-layouts/2010-2019/
  3. Birthday: FiveThirtyEight, ABC News
    • Link: https://github.com/fivethirtyeight/data/blob/master/births/US_births_2000-2014_SSA.csv

Analysis¶

First, we learned from these resources that only knowing personal information on zip-code, gender, age, or birthday is hardly sufficient to successfully identify any individual. That said, there is a reasonable chance of identifying certain groups of individuals by knowing zip-code. Second, if an individual’s records on all four variables were available, identifying a small group of individuals or uniquely identifying one individual becomes possible with reasonable certainty.

An inspection of the population distribution by gender in 2019 (Fig. 2.3) reveals an almost equal distribution, with the female population slightly larger than the male. This suggests that knowing the gender of an individual would only exclude half of the US population, and thus this personal information is not particularly helpful in terms of identifying a certain group of individuals or directly identifying a single individual. This phenomenon applies to the US birthday dataset we found as well. Fig. 3.1 illustrates an approximately equal distribution of the US birth population across different years (from 2000-2014), and the number of possible people under consideration is still extremely huge when attempting to pinpoint any specific group or individuals. While it is true that knowing the specific date of birth (e.g., 2014-1-1) would narrow potential identities down to around 10,000 individuals, the possibility of determining a single identification is still unreasonable. What’s more, examining the graph of the US estimation of 2019 population distribution on age (Fig. 2.2), we detected a unimodal and right-skewed distribution, leaving us with the impression that it may be possible to identify very elderly outliers. A close look at the dataset, nevertheless, reveals that there were more than 50,000 individuals who were 100 years old in 2019, making it unlikely to identify certain groups of individuals or one particular individual with confidence using age as the determining variable.

However, knowing the zip code of an individual depicts a different story. We can learn from Fig. 1 that the US population distribution on zip codes is multimodal, with some zip codes containing more residents than others. This suggests that residents in certain areas are more vulnerable to re-identification than others, especially those in communities with very few residents. For example, the zip code 02216 is a very small community in Suffolk County, MA, with only 17 residents in 2015. Consequently, the number of possible people under consideration is relatively small, making identification possible with reasonable certainty. Admittedly, knowing zip code information alone is still insufficient to uniquely identify an individual outside of these specific conditions.

So is it possible to directly identify an individual with a combination of the above pieces of information? Before digging into our response to this question, it is worth noting that since we were unable to find large and diverse datasets in which an individual’s information on zip code, gender, age, and birthday are recorded all at once or could be recognized by joining different datasets, we performed a hypothetical analysis based on the resources we did find. With that in mind, we argue that identification with reasonable certainty is very likely to be realized, assuming we have knowledge of all four basic demographic variables. However, identification is not a certainty and depends on the number of people residing in a zip code, as well as the age and birthday distributions in said ZIP population.

For example, if a zip code has a small population like the one illustrated above with 17 residents, we could easily identify a specific individual by their gender and age if the distribution of age is unimodal (like the dataset we found), especially if they are an outlier. However, even if the population is relatively homogenous such that most of the residents are between the ages of 40-49 yrs, this would not pose a significant challenge given our dataset, as the variable is as precise as a single year difference. More directly, we could easily identify a specific individual by their birthday, given the low probability of two persons being born on the same date in a small population. However, to examine an opposing example, if a zip code has a large population (e.g., 01075; a community with 14590 residents in Hampshire County, MA), the percentage of its population considered identifiable will decrease considerably when compared to those zip codes with much smaller populations. This is because the number of people under consideration for each gender and age subgroup becomes larger and the zip population passes the threshold of minimum people required to guarantee at least two of them were born on exactly the same date. This being said, there still remains the possibility of identifying individuals uniquely if they are outliers in the age distribution and could, therefore, be identified by their much more unique birth date.

After getting a general idea of different data types, we divide our variables into four groups, int64, object, bool and float64.

Data Type of Int64¶

There is 1 variable with the data type of int64.

1 - user_id: it's a direct identifier. Because it includes information that relates specifically to an individual. This can identify an individual on its own.

Data Type of Object¶

There are 38 variables with the data type of object. We mainly combine data description and the function check_unilink we write to check whether it's a direct identifiers or quasi-identifiers.

check_unilink function groups the data by the values of var1 and further check whether the values of var2 is distinct in each group of var1. Since NULL might have different meanings in different variables, we ignore NULL values here. When we get the result that var1 is uniquely linked with var2, we would further check the variable to see whether NULL has influence on the classification of the variable.

In [28]:
# check whether var1 is uniquely linked with var2
def check_unilink(data, var1, val2):
    data_group = data.groupby(by = [var1])
    for name, group in data_group:
        if len(set(list(group[val2].values))) != 1 and not group[val2].isnull().values.any():
            print(name)
            print(group.loc[:, [val2]])
            return var1 + " is not uniquely linked with " + val2
    return var1 + " is uniquely linked with " + val2

0 - course_id: course_id refers to course ID in the standard format as org/number/semester. Through the check_unilink function, we found that course_id is not uniquely linked with user_id, meaning that one certain course can be taken by multiple users in the edX system. That said, couse_id can be used as an identifier to narrow the whole range of users to certain ones that have taken this course, and by combining this variable with other variables such as age, gender, region, and etc., as well as by examining the combination of different courses, there is a reasonable chance of identifying a specific person in the system. We can thus conclude that course_id is not a direct identifier but a quasi-identifier and it is a categorical variable.

2 - username: it's a quasi identifier. Because username is not uniquely linked with user_id. People with different user_id have different username. It's categorical quasi-identifier

5 - explored: explored indicates whether the user viewed at least half of the chapters of the course (True) or not (False). Through the check_unilink function, we found that explored is not uniquely linked with user_id, meaning that multiple users viewed or didn’t view at least half of a course’s chapter. That said, explored can be used as an identifier to divide the whole range of users into two groups: those that have viewed and not viewed, and by combining this variable with other variables such as courses being taken, identification would be possible with reasonable certainty. We can thus conclude that explored is not a direct identifier but a quasi-identifier and it is a categorical variable.

By then, this variable would be a quasi-identifier, as in combination with other variables such as zip code and gender, identification would be possible with reasonable certainty.

50 - verified_unenroll_time, referring to the time when a user initially had their last id-verified un-enrollment event, if applicable, and NULL is never enrolled. Through the check_unilink function, we found that verified_unenroll_time uniquely linked with user_id. This suggests that one single value of the variable is directly linked to a specific user_id. However, according to the description, there is a considerable number of users who have never unenrolled in the course and are coded as NULL. With this in mind, verified_unenroll_time can be used to directly identify a user only when it has a valid value. Otherwise, it should be treated as a quasi-identifier, as it helps narrow the whole range of users down to those that do not have applicable data for verified_unenroll_time. And by combining this information with other variables, identification would be possible with reasonable certainty.

51 - profile_country refers to two-letter country code as specified by a user in their profile (only available after ~mid-2014). Through the check_unilink function, we found that profile_country is not uniquely linked with user_id, meaning that such information (e.g., AD) can be linked to multiple users. That said, profile_country can be used as an identifier to divide the whole range of users into subgroups of people who not only joined the edX system after ~mid-2014 and but are located in different countries, and by combining this variable with other demographic variables such as zip code and gender, there is a reasonable chance of identifying a specific user. We can thus conclude that profile_country is not a direct identifier but a quasi-identifier and it is a categorical variable.

53 - The same logic applies to the variable email_domain, which refers to the domain of the email address of the user, with the exception that this variable allows narrowing the whole range of users down to those with the same email domain. email_domain is a categorical variable.

Summary¶

Quasi-identifiers are pieces of information that are not of themselves unique identifiers, but are sufficiently well correlated with an entity that they can be combined with other quasi-identifiers to uniquely identify an individual. Based on our analysis above, we conclude that the direct identifiers are ‘user_id’ and ‘verified_enroll_time’.

Categorical quasi-identifiers include ‘username’, ‘explored’, ‘ip’, ‘cc_by_ip’, ‘countryLabel’, ‘city’, ‘region’, ‘subdivision’, ‘postalCode’, ‘un_major_region’, ‘un_economic_group’,, ‘un_special_region’, ‘LoE’, ‘gender’, ‘start_time’, ‘first_event’, ‘last_event’, ‘roles’, ‘mode’, ‘cert_created_date’, ‘cert_modified_date’, ‘cert_status’, ‘profile_country’, ‘email_domain’, ‘language_brwsr’, ‘language_brwsr_country’, ‘viewed’, ‘certified’, ‘completed’, language_brwsr_sec_country’, ‘language_brwsr_code’, ‘language_brwsr_subcode’, ‘language_brwsr_sec_code’, ‘language_brwsr_sec_subcode’, ‘language’, ‘is_active’, ‘y1_anomalous’, ‘roles_isBetaTester’, ‘roles_isInstructor’, ‘roles_isStaff’, ‘roles_isFinance’, ‘roles_isSales’, ‘forumRoles_isModerator’, and ‘forumRoles_isStudent’.
